elements.contents: private Library user32; private long appHandle; public void sendRequest() { long requestMsgId = (int)this.registerWindowMessage("WM_TBD_SN_REQEST"); long responseMsgId = (int)this.registerWindowMessage("WM_TBD_SN_RESPONSE"); long tbdHandle = findWindow(null, "TestApp"); this.sendWindowsMessage(new Handle(tbdHandle), new Int(requestMsgId), new Handle(this.appHandle), new Pointer.Void()); } public long sendWindowsMessage(final Parameter... args) { final Function sendMessage = this.user32.getFunction("SendMessageA"); LongInt longInt = new LongInt(); sendMessage.invoke(longInt, args); return longInt.getValue(); } public long findWindow(final String classname, final String windowName) { final Function findWindow = this.user32.getFunction("FindWindowA"); Parameter cName = null; if (classname == null || classname.equals("")) { cName = new Pointer.Void(); } else { cName = new AnsiString(classname); } LongInt longInt = new LongInt(); findWindow.invoke(longInt, cName, new AnsiString(windowName)); return longInt.getValue(); } public long registerWindowMessage(String message) { final Function findWindow = this.user32.getFunction("RegisterWindowMessageA"); LongInt longInt = new LongInt(); findWindow.invoke(longInt, new AnsiString(message)); return longInt.getValue(); }

node.contents: The WM_COPYDATA message sends a pointer to (that is the address of a) COPYDATASTRUCT which is defined by Windows as:

astNode.text: The WM_COPYDATA message sends a pointer to (that is the address of a) COPYDATASTRUCT which is defined by Windows as:

elements.contents: struct COPYDATASTRUCT { ULONG_PTR dwData; DWORD cbData; PVOID lpData; }

units.rawText: struct COPYDATASTRUCT { ULONG_PTR dwData; DWORD cbData; PVOID lpData; }

node.contents: From Java you will have to read this manually using the methods in the sun.misc.Unsafe class. By manually I mean you will have to calculate the memory addresses yourself.

astNode.text: From Java you will have to read this manually using the methods in the sun.misc.Unsafe class. By manually I mean you will have to calculate the memory addresses yourself.

node.contents: dwData is an integer value the application can use for itself. lpData is a pointer to a buffer holding data that the application wanted to pass. cbData is the number of bytes in the buffer that lpData contains.

astNode.text: dwData is an integer value the application can use for itself. lpData is a pointer to a buffer holding data that the application wanted to pass. cbData is the number of bytes in the buffer that lpData contains.

node.contents: In Windows a ULONG_PTR is 4 bytes on a 32 bit system and 8 bytes on a 64 bit system. A DWORD is 4 bytes always. A PVOID, which is a pointer (i.e. a memory address) is 4 bytes on a 32 bit system and 8 bytes on a 64 bit system.

astNode.text: In Windows a ULONG_PTR is 4 bytes on a 32 bit system and 8 bytes on a 64 bit system. A DWORD is 4 bytes always. A PVOID, which is a pointer (i.e. a memory address) is 4 bytes on a 32 bit system and 8 bytes on a 64 bit system.

node.contents: So on a 32 bit system dwData is at offset 0, cbData at offset 4, and lpData at offset 8. On a 64 bit system dwData is still at offset 0, but cbData is at offset 8, and lpData at offset 16.

astNode.text: So on a 32 bit system dwData is at offset 0, cbData at offset 4, and lpData at offset 8. On a 64 bit system dwData is still at offset 0, but cbData is at offset 8, and lpData at offset 16.

elements.contents: import sun.misc; final int dwDataOffset = 0; final int cbDataOffset = 4; // Change to 8 for 64 bit final int lpDataOffset = 8; // Change to 16 for 64 bit int cpDataAddr = this._pData.getValue(); // This will return the address of the struct (I assume this syntax is correct) - change to long for 64 bit int messageCode= Unsafe.getInt(cpDataAddr+dwDataOffset); // Change to getLong for 64 bit int dataSize = Unsafe.getInt(cbDataAddr+cbDataOffset); int dataAddress = Unsafe.GetInt(cbDataAddr+lpDataOffset); // Change to getLong for 64 bit // Create a buffer to hold the data from lpData byte[] data = new byte[dataSize]; for (int i = 0; i < dataSize; i++) data[i] = Unsafe.getByte(dataAddress+i);

node.contents: There is a much easier way to send messages between a Java application and a C# application. Use ZeroMQ messages using the TCP transport tcp://127.0.0.1:portnum The ZeroMQ guide http://zguide.zeromq.org/page:all shows dozens of examples of communication patterns that yu can implement with only a few lines of code.

node.contents: Some people don't use it because it does not support the IPC transport on Windows, but it does support the TCP transport and that works just fine as an IPC solution because the kernel recognizes that it is a local destination and shortcuts the unneeded TCP/IP stack processing.

node.contents: You mentioned that you are trying to control a C# program for which you have no access to the source code. This type of thing is often called screen-scraping, and you might be better off by writing a simple C# application using Managed Spy or some C++ code using Spy++ to act as an intermediary for your Java application.
